article.description: Jess Brungo scored 19 points, and Penn State withstood a late run by Wisconsin for a 66-50 victory Thursday night.
article.headline: Brungo scores 19 points for Lady Lions
article.linkText: No. 7 Penn State easily beats Wisconsin
article.story:
STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) -- Penn State coach Rene Portland was
ecstatic about being able to stand on the sidelines for the first
time in two months. Her excitement faded when her Lady Lions nearly
squandered a big lead in the second half.

Jess Strom hit six late free throws, and seventh-ranked Penn
State withstood a late run by Wisconsin for a 66-50 victory
Thursday night.

"The biggest disappointment tonight was, obviously, a lack of
offense for about a seven-minute span in the second half -- a lack
of rebounding effort, where we just got one shot and it was
one-and-done," Portland said. "We got a win, and we're headed
down the next road, but obviously we have some things that we
really need to attack."

It was Portland's first game on two feet since she slipped on
ice and broke her left leg Dec. 18. She coached the last 15 games
either in a wheelchair or a cart.

Penn State's last field goal was Jess Brungo's 3-pointer, which
made it 60-36 with 7:27 left.

"I think we were running through our stuff just to run it,"
Brungo said. "We were getting shots, but not the shots we wanted
to get."

Jordan Wilson scored twice to start a 14-0 run by the Badgers,
and Ashley Josephson's 3-pointer brought Wisconsin (8-15, 2-11 Big
Ten) to 60-50 with 2:40 left. However, Strom went 6-for-6 from the
line in the last 1:02 and the Lady Lions (20-4, 12-1) pulled away
for the win.

The Badgers three chances close within single digits, but turned
the ball over twice before Strom's first set of free throws, then
missed two 3-pointers in the final minute.

"If one of those 3s drop in, we cut a 10-point lead to seven,
or maybe even four," Wisconsin coach Lisa Stone said. "We had a
never-say-die attitude. We showed some character, some courage and
commitment tonight, and I'm very proud of my team for playing all
40 minutes."

The Lady Lions built their lead by driving the lane, attacking
regardless of whether Wisconsin was playing zone or man-to-man.

In the second half, the Badgers started switching on screens,
and Penn State couldn't penetrate.

"They were switching on everything," Portland said. "I don't
think we did attack, didn't put the ball on the floor, didn't put
the ball in the basket. And we had some people who were just
running plays flat out wrong, and that really hurts us."

Brungo led Penn State with 18 points, Tanisha Wright scored 17,
and Kelly Mazzante -- sporting a knee brace for the first time this
season -- added 15. Strom had 10 points.

"I guess I should be thrilled four players are in double
figures, but then you look at the rest and they only add up to six
points," Portland said. "We have to be very, very concerned about
our offense and where we're getting our offense from."

Emily Ashbaugh led Wisconsin with 14 points, and Josephson
scored 10.

Wisconsin kept it close for about five minutes, pulling to 12-11
on Wilson's hook shot with 15:12 left in the first half.

But Wright scored the next two baskets, starting a 12-0 run that
gave Penn State a permanent double-digit lead. Brungo hit two in a
row, the second a 3-pointer, in an 8-0 run that made it 38-19 late
in the first half. The Lady Lions led 40-23 at the break.
